	ZORTECH OS/2 MULTITHREADED LIBRARY SUPPORT

This version adds support for multithreaded libraries under OS/2 1.x.

The new functions in the library are:
	_beginthread()
	_endthread()
which are equivalent to the MSC counterparts. We recommend that you
use these functions to fire off threads, rather than DOSCREATETHREAD(),
as these functions handle the synchronization necessary for the
runtime libraries.

To build a multithreaded program, no special libraries are needed.
We felt that since most OS/2 programs were multithreaded, we dispensed
with the clumsiness of a separate library, and made the basic libraries
all multithreaded. The multithreading support is enabled in the
.h files by the macro:
	#define _MT	1
We recommend if you are building multithreading programs, you
define _MT to 1 (this is compatible with MSC 6 too). Note that
__OS2__ is also defined. This is because in the future we expect
multithreading support to appear under many more operating systems,
so it is best to have a separate #define for it.

Multithreading is supported in all the OS/2 memory models s,m,c,l.

So, to build a multithreaded program:

	ZTC -D__OS2__ -D_MT program

Some performance degradation is impossible to avoid with multithreading
the libraries. In particular, malloc/free and fputc/fgetc may be
slower. If you do not intend to do storage allocation in any thread
other than the primary thread, or the same for stdio, you can get
rid of the performance penalty by recompiling ALLOC.ASM and FPUTC.ASM
*without* defining _MT, and then link them in explicitly.

Libraries can be created that can be linked both to multithreading
OS/2 and to DOS programs without recompiling. Compile them with
_MT. The OLDSTR?.LIB libraries are built this way.

For examples on how to do multithread synchronization, see PUTENV.C,
GETENV.ASM, FCLOSE.C, FPUTC.ASM and ALLOC.ASM.
The other library routines we tried hard to make them reentrant so
they did not need synchronization. (sprintf is fully reentrant!)

